  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (Title 18, U.S. Code, Sections 1956 and 1957). Penalties can include hefty fines and significant prison sentences. Similarly, most countries have stringent laws and enforcement mechanisms to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**.\n\nKey aspects of money laundering laws typically include:\n\n1. **Prohibiting the act of laundering funds** obtained through illegal activities.\n2. **Requiring financial institutions** to report suspicious transactions and maintain records.\n3. **Imposing penalties** on individuals and businesses involved in money laundering.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal advice immediately. Engaging in such activities can lead to severe legal consequences.",
